segments.text: Well, say your name again and tell me about your father.
Well, my name is... Now?
Yes.
My name is Graviela Gámez.
Yes.
And I am the daughter of Juan Gámez Sr. and my mother, Mrs. Ramona R. Gámez.
My mother was Reyes for her father.
I am Reyes Gámez.
Well, my father was a military man in Mexico when he was a carranza.
He was a carrancista.
They called them carrancistas.
He was a carrancista soldier in Mexico.
That's why they came to give the rosary, because that's where all the troops were stationed.
And that's when they fought and won Matamoros.
That's why from Ciudad Victoria to Matamoros is Tamaulipas.
It's the state of Tamaulipas, Mexico.
Because they won the war back then.
I don't know when the war started.
I think it was 1910.
It was the first year.
Well, it was when I was born.
I was a baby.
Not a very small baby.
I was a girl.
I was born in 1910.
I was born on March 18.
And my father was in the militia, in the war.
He was...
Soldado.
¿Para qué razón entró?
Bueno, pues como aquí, you know, lo llama el gobierno, tiene que ir.
Y allá lo llamó el gobierno, aunque eran hombres familiares, pero tuvieron que, necesidad de ir, porque eran, tenían, llevaban los soldados, los reclutaban como aquí.
Es la razón que fueron.
Aquí hay muchos jóvenes que no quieren ir y tienen que ir.
Because the government calls them.
What can they do with the government?
They have to go to the government to serve the country.
And in Mexico, it's the same thing.
That's why my father was a militant.
He was a lieutenant.
He was a very humble man, but he did everything very correctly.
My uncles, my mother's brothers, were also soldiers at that time.
One was the clarinet player, you know, the one who plays the clarinet so that all the soldiers get up.
And the other, my uncle, the other, José, was the one who carried the flag.
Yes.
But there in Mexico, my mother said, all the soldiers were all horsemen, they walked on horses, you know.
They were horsemen.
They were horsemen.
That's how they were called, horsemen.
And the ones who brought the other one, as they say, Pancho V was very brave.
But all of his poor soldiers were brought on foot.
They fought, all on foot.
But your father was a horse rider.
Oh, my father, yes.
My father rode horses, all of them.
They were horse riders.
They were horse soldiers.
That's the name.
Horse soldiers, not infantry.
The infantry are the ones who go on foot, the poor ones.
Like your father.
Your family wasn't from the poor.
Well, my father was a farmer.
Yes.
A man who worked in the fields.
But they don't call them labores here.
They call them potreros.
For example, the owner says, I'm going to take a look at the work.
And in Mexico, he says, I'm going to take a look at the potrero to see how the land is so they can start working.
That's what they say in Mexico.
Well, my mom used to tell us.
I wasn't very young.
I looked at how my father worked in Mexico, but my mother didn't.
My father used to talk about why they came here to make the rosary.
And from there they worked, they came here to work.
And then my father sent to bring my mother to Padilla.
He wrote to her, he told her to get ready because he was going to bring her.
You know, sobrinos y familia de la...
sisters and all that.
But the elders of the family, the parents, the older sisters, they all died.
My mother has a sister.
We have an aunt in Mexico, in Padilla.
She's my mother's sister.
She came here about 8 or 9 years ago.
Yes, because she came after my father and my mother died.
She came to see us.
She has a lot that came and she didn't come.
But she lives.
She writes to us here and there.
She sends us a letter.
So that she knows about us.
It's the whole family that we have on my mother's side.
What kind of stories did your father tell about his days as a soldier?
Soldier?
I don't know, because I think he only talked to my mother.
I think.
We were younger.
Yes.
The little ones don't pay attention to what the parents or the mother talk about.
Yes.
They're going to play, or they're going to do what they're told to do.
No.
Yes, he was a soldier.
He fought in Mexico.
He fought here.
I have three nephews in the service.
One was in Thailand.
The other one was in Thailand a month ago.
He was there for a year.
And the other one...
But the revolution was especially hard, right?
Yes, my mom says so.
And what did your mother do during those years when your father was a soldier?
Well, they left them there in the house.
They left them there and when they could, they sent them money so they could buy their food.
That was all.
They didn't go with him?
No, they stayed there in the farm, in the house.
But they were very afraid.
Because in Mexico, it wasn't the same war as here.
In Mexico, suddenly, in the middle of the night, all the people were sleeping, peaceful.
The people who were civilians, peaceful.
And suddenly, when they woke up, the soldiers arrived.
That's why my mother was very afraid.
All the families, all of them.
My grandmothers cried a lot for them because
My father's grandmother had already passed away, but my grandmother lived with my mother because she worked with her two children and her son-in-law, my father, in the war.
Many families, all the poor families, their husbands, their brothers, their children did not come.
In the militia?
Yes.
In Mexico they say in the militia, those who are in the war, they tell us, you're in the war, or you're a soldier, or you're in the militia, or you're in the militia, you're a soldier.
A soldier.
A soldier is a soldier who fights with weapons.
It was very hard.
My mother said that the war in Mexico was very hard.
Very, very hard.
And when...
No, it was in 1909.
When there was an abduction in Mexico.
Yes.
They named him Cyclone.
Yes.
In what year?
It was before the war.
Yes, I think so.
It was when my grandmother died because she was very scared.
It was when my...
Mi hermana chiquita, no, yo creo fue menos después, porque mi hermana nació en 1905, el 25 de febrero.
Mi hermana es la que está en el pueblo, la mayor de la familia.
Y la inundación esa fue en 1909, un año antes que naciera yo.
Because my sister was brought up in Chiquita.
And my mother says that it didn't rain.
Suddenly it didn't rain, it was just that the water came to the houses and they came to warn us.
That there was a very big crescent.
Like when the river comes out here.
My mother told me that the trees in the houses did not look so good.
And they were very afraid because my aunt, my father's little sister, had gone to the ranch with one of her sisters and my grandmother, my father's mother.
And there, in the ranch, the crescent fished them.
And they started to warn us to leave the houses.
They went up to where they were very high, high, if not the highest, because the water was coming up very cold.
And my aunt said that when they left the house, she would give the water to Sina.
And she brought a baby of a month of birth, my aunt, my little sister and my father.
And I know that they left, and they left where there were high and high, and the more bad it was, the water was here and here.
In the body?

Yes, they were walking through the mountain, and then there were some very large trees, and a man who was their brother-in-law, a brother of a brother-in-law of my uncle and my father, he was a very good swimmer.
So he put up a lot of sticks and made them into sticks.
And all the families went up there.
He said there were 30 families who spent three days there.
Three days?
30 families?
Yes, on those sticks.
And my mother, my grandmother, was going to take my mother's baby, my little sister.
They brought something to give to the children.
My grandmother cooked for them.
She said, God, where are we going?
We are going to cook something for these children.
They cooked rice, you know, and they put all the juice in a jar to bring to the children.
Bebitos to give them.
Because my grandmother took my mother's bebito.
My little sister had a bebito.
She was a month or two months old.
And there they spent three days and four nights on top of the sticks.
My mother here in the farm and other women, all the families of the other women, crying because they didn't know if they had drowned or not.
My mother said that they passed the trees, the rivers gathered, all the rivers.
The river, I don't know what that river is called, that is in Padilla.
I don't know its name, it has a name.
And there's a river that my mom says is very big, and that river grows all the time with a lot of water.
It's called the Corona River.
They got together and all the water came.
It was when they say that... That water came from Tocante, they say that a hill was blown up.
I don't know what it is in Monterrey, that has a lot of water.
And it blew up.
That was the flood that happened.
I said, mom, there were a lot of people who had no houses.
And they had adobe houses, you know, adobe houses, you know, the ones they had.
And the water would get to the shore like this, because the river was very close.
They said that the waves of water would come and they would do like this.
And it got all wet, but they said, mom, we didn't think it would get wet at all.
The only thing that made us strong was your father and my little creature and your mother and all the people.
There were 30 families and all of them were in the mosques up there.
Yes.
When it started to go down, I saw the mosques and the trees.
I saw that the mosques, the trees, only the tips of the branches were removed.
Yes.
It was a very ugly, very ugly, very big, very big, at that time, my mother.
And that's when it started, when they saw that they started to go down a little bit.
And then, between more and more, another day, it got lower and lower, so that man went down, because he was very good at swimming.
And he said, let's see if I can reach Plan.
We reached Plan.
We looked for a way to cross the river, to see if we could cross over to Papadilla.
They go, and he went down and reached a little bit of Plano.
And we reached Plano, and it was him, and another man, and a brother of my mother's.
And my grandmother didn't want him to leave because she thought he was going to drown.
And he said, you're going to drown, Maximiano.
No, no, Grandma, no, no, my son.
May God help us.
And they left.
And they went to swim there.
My mom said that they arrived like at 3 in the afternoon, in the middle of the water.
But they arrived to see how the people were doing and to give them reason.
And they said that they were all crying, all the women were crying.
Some for their children, some for their husbands, some for their sisters, for their daughters.
And then they arrived and said, well, where did they come from?
Where did they come from?
Where did they come from?
We have them there, don't take care of them, they're good.
But we came to bring them food, because there are those innocent people without food.
And now the children are small.
But when they went out there to Padilla, where the $100 store was, he said that he already gave them the water here, and that was going down there.
And then they left, they went to talk to the administrator, and he sent a lot of people, the administrator,
so that they could save those families.
And there were many people, men, to such an extent that when they arrived and then from there they were going to bring them, to cross them one by one, to bring them.
And on the shore that they knew was on the shore of the river, there they had some skiff to cross with the families.
And that's how they crossed them.
And my aunt didn't want to go down because she was afraid.
She was the first baby she had.
And when she went down, the baby fell into the water.
my aunt's baby, and she screamed, my aunt was very angry, and my aunt went to grab the baby, but she didn't know how to swim, so she caught it.
Then the other lady grabbed the baby and took it out.
It didn't drown, but it did drown.
And that was when my grandmother, my mother and my father got very scared and died.
They died of pure heart attack.
She saw a lot of water.
She said she didn't see the trees.
You couldn't see the low trees.
Only the tall ones.
And they spent three days and four nights in that.
She said they had the pieces in the water.
But the sticks that the gentlemen put were very solid.
They tied them very solid.
It was as if they were up there.
And so many days.
My mother would tell us, and I don't even want to remember, but normally I tell them to know how we suffered.
How we suffered.
Your father suffered with his mother in Tantahui, with your aunt, and your other aunt.
Two sisters of my father were there.
My father and my grandmother.
And my mother here alone.
and my grandmother, my mother's mother, they were here in Hacienda Dolores.
I mean, just waiting for them to tell them that they had drowned, because they couldn't, because many drowned, my mother, many people drowned.
Because they took the whole houses, they took the houses, they went through the middle of the river, going around the houses.
Many people went inside, they drowned.
That's why they were afraid, and they were afraid of,
They were afraid of them here, and they were afraid of them there.
They didn't know where they were or how they were.
They didn't know if they would have been taken by the water.
My mom said it was very heavy.
They said it was a cyclone, but it didn't rain much.
It started to rain and it stopped, but the water kept coming up and up and up until it covered some houses.
It didn't go up there because it was too high in the hacienda.
They said it was too high.
It was too high.
In the hacienda too?
In the hacienda Dolores.
They said it only went up to a certain part.
And it went up.
And very little, to some houses it went up, because it was too low.
I don't even want to remember, but I'll tell you so you know how we suffered.

We suffered because your father left and took your little sister, your grandmother, because she took good care of her, and your grandmother, and your other aunt, and your other aunt, and a brother of mine, and the rest were well-known families, families from the ranch that were there, they all got together.
But my mom said, well, how could your grandmother not be dead?
She said that after two months of that, my grandmother died.
Because she was very surprised to be so alone and to see so much water.
And she thought that just as they were there, there would be those who were there.
And my grandmother died.
The mother of my father.
My father was a very good man.
This cyclone here in Corpus Christi in 19...1919?
Do you remember this?
No, I don't remember.
I was more in the middle.
How old was that little girl?
I think I had like...
Nine years, more or less.
About eight years.
Eight years, yes.
But I don't see much, because I was with an aunt of mine, and we spent time in a house, but she was at a table, like, oh, there's a girl, and there we were, me and another little sister of mine.
So we didn't see much.
I know Celia, who came now.
Yes, yes.
I didn't see her.
No?
The other one that came, the first one, what's her name?
Celia.
Celia, but she came...
Yes, but another one came.
The first one.
What's the other one called?
She also has a name of a woman.
The first one, and then came Celia.
Celia was the one who... Well, I didn't see her.
No?
No, because I worked with Mrs. Kepp, Miss Kepp.
So she was in a small closet, and we went up there because her house was very elegant.
Her house was very elegant, very tall.
Like this one, it had a floor down and a floor up.
And they started to fall, like those windows, all down.
All of them.
And the water inside was so high.
She started to come in and she grabbed me and two other boys that she had and the little boy.
We got into a closet and she said, no, don't go because I don't know what's going to happen.
She said, if you want to go home, don't kill us.
Don't kill the girls.
So we were there, in the closet, locked up.
So I didn't forget how I was.

After it was all over, we went out to see, and on the streets I saw pure things like this, electric coffee machines, bread toasters, well, full of pure trash on the streets, from where the houses were.
Very terrible.
And I don't forget.
And the other day they said that a tornado was coming and I said, playing with my sister, ah, well, let Pabelo come.
I've never seen a chubasco like that.
And Jonevitas, as I remember, said, well, yes, well, he left a lot of everything, a lot of bodies, it was pure board, wherever, in the streets.
Do you have fear of other things?
Oh, yes.
Yes, a lot?
Well, yes, because that's how Corpus Christi was, very cheap.
There are many houses that have just been built, and it's been three years since I've been here.
My brother lives here on this side.
His house, his blankets, his clothes, all the clothes that they put on were well made because they had ironed them.
The mattresses and the curtains didn't fit at all.
The doors didn't fit at all.
The windows, just the doors.
My brother didn't fit at all.
He was very scared.
They said he was screaming a lot.
He was screaming a lot.
He grabbed the smallest one and he squeezed her.
And he has one.
And the girl got married.
She just started to see the water and the doors opened and she fainted.
Because he was very scared.
She fainted and she was fine.
Super.
And Pancho was already struggling with her and Manuel with the two little ones here, grabbing them.
and a little girl and a daughter who were there with him.
I also had three of them.
And then I couldn't attend to the doors, and I said, Manuel, let the doors be taken away, just don't let a creature get in.
I take care of my children.
God help us, all the clothes go away.
Yes, the pieces of sheets and mattresses were on the side of the street.
God didn't leave them anything.
I said, well, thank God that he brought the clothes, but they didn't do anything, I don't see any of his family.
No one turned around.
Is it possible to make preparations before the next cyclone?
Is there anything for people to do?
I don't know what they can do.
They have given many instructions on the radio to say how to do it.
What can they do?

They were saying that when a tornado comes, if they think that their house is not very powerful to resist that air, that they go out into the street where there are no trees, and if they see a very strong storm of air, because that's what comes most in those tornadoes, air than water, right?
that they fall on the ground and get really strong.
On the ground, better.
Because in the house, a stick falls.
That's how people get killed.
A stick or something falls and hits them.
A window frame.
That's what the man says when he gives the advice for hurricanes, for...
For tornadoes.
But tornadoes are ugly because they go around like this.
It's a...
It's a whirlwind, right?
Yes.
A whirlwind of air.
A whirlwind.
Yes, it's a whirlwind.
There are hurricanes and...
The hurricane is a hurricane air, but it also brings a lot of water.
Yes.
And these tornadoes do bring water, but not a lot.
What they bring is a lot of air, like this, back and forth.
Yes.
And after it passes, there's water.
Yes.
That's what happens.
It seems that a tornado is worse than a chubaco.
A chubaco?
Chubasco.
What is this?
Chubasco is a very strong water with a lot of air that sweeps the trees like this.
Do you see how the cell fell?
Yes, it's the same thing as a hurricane.
Chubasco and hurricane are the same thing.
It's just that the hurricane is stronger because the air comes much stronger.
The hurricane.
And the chubasco comes strong, but the air comes with water.
So it's not...
It's not that strong because in parts when the water falls, it cuts the air a little, you know?
It cuts the air a little.
And the hurricane, no, it comes sweeping everything because the water comes as strong as the air.
It's almost the same as the tornado, the hurricane.
The hurricane is strong.
And yesterday they were saying, talking, reporting that
It's a tropical storm.
Tropical is very strong water and air, like a hurricane, the tropical one.
Well, now they give names to people.
A friend of mine,
She has a sister named Celia.
I said to Celia, I don't love you.
I said to Dred, playing, I don't love you.
She said, why?
Because your name is Celia.
And Celia was very terrible here with us.
How could she leave us?
She left a lot of people without... My kids, where I worked, they had here, to Sandia, to one side of El Naranjo.
They have a ranch, not very big, about 40 acres.
And they had a very nice trailer.
Y le estaban pegando corredor de pura tela para cuando iban a pasar día de campo.
Estaba muy fresco y no se metían los zancudos ni nada.
Pues no las dejó nada.
Se las barrió, las trae, las contó y todo.
Hace una semana que le había ido a poner cortinas nuevas y todo para ahora que venga el summer para ir a pasar una semana allá o dos.
Le dijo, y te vamos a llevar a ti también, dijo, para que te vayas con nosotros a pasear allá.
Well, Celia came and she didn't leave anything for them.
The pots, the pans, the pans, they were found in the labors buried in the ground.
And she didn't leave anything for them.
A house that they had, they lost a lot, those gentlemen.
Their house was almost all sold out.
And only the room where I slept, where the child slept,
He didn't break a window, he didn't get wet, he didn't do anything.
But where the girls slept, where the lady slept, there was nothing left.
He had a big mirror, like this one.
He had the sign to wash himself.
Like this, the big mirror.
There was nothing left.
Las cortinas, las ventanas, nomás los cuadros sin vidrio, las ventanas, las cortinas, todas las sacó, las bolas y las aventó para afuera.
Todo.
Y la que tenían en por el antes para ir a pasar días de campo, cuando iban a pescar, la señora dice que nomás un montón de madera.
Ellos perdieron mucho.
He became very bad, despite the fact that he lost a lot of money.
He's a doctor, however he wants to call it.
He already has all his land, and he loses money, however he wants to call it.
That's the money he spends, right?
To buy that.
I used to cry a lot there, when I was in my room.
Don't cry, your people are good at saying yes.
But I don't know how they are doing.
And I don't know my house.
He said my house didn't fall.
Nothing fell.
He took a window.
He broke a glass window and took a cloth.
The doors, at the time, like three months or four months after it had happened, they started to break down due to the humidity of the water.
They started to fall, the doors, but it was all.
I saw how it was, and the roof from above, from outside, it also started to fall, the one that was supposed to be on the roof.
But for it to fall, no.
or that my bed or my things would get wet.
They didn't get wet.
And a lady, a young lady, who wanted a house that was almost the same and with the same accompaniment, they didn't have anything left.
They only had a chair, like this one here, a chair like this one that was standing.
That was all that was left.
In my house.
And all the people say, why was she so lucky?
She didn't even get her house wet.
And the man says, Chihuahua, look what a lucky girl.
We have a lot of boards.
And mine doesn't.
But maybe mine has a lot of trees.
They say that's why.
That the trees helped her a lot.

how to stop the air, because there is a tree on this side, there are some oranges on this side, and on this side, I had, since I moved in, those little trees were born, when my father and mother lived, they were like this, little ones, they were born, and they were made like this,
They were very curious.
They grew together, very tangled.
And when Celia took them out, she took one with all the roots and the other one was left there.
But it was all the damage she did.
The tree fell on the edge of the roof of the house and took a big piece of that board that was thrown at the house by the edge.
It was all the damage that he did to my house.
The window that fell, the fabric, the glass that broke, and the tree that he took out, he took it out with three roots.
And he took it out.
But he was very curious, he looked at me like that, and I told him how I was.
Because they were born together.
And they were made like that.
That's how he was.
Let me say it.
I was talking and cutting this because I have to cut it.
I'm going to make enchiladas.
You already ate.
What?
You already ate.
